snippet.textDisplay: With out part two of this out yet, here is my 2 cents.   Would the new Spiderman be as awesome if not for his amazing performances in the MCU? Sony needs the MCU to really keep Tom Holland's Spidey going.  People don't just love the Spider-Man they love his relationship with Tony Stark. It was a Sony movie that pointed to Spider-Man beating the new Avengers. But Stony can't follow that story line with out disney.  Could the MCU work with out Spidey?  Sure.  It did for quite some time.  But we all loved spidey and Tony father figure relationship.

snippet.textDisplay:
You're forgetting that the marketing budget is listed separately from the production budget and film companies usually describe the cost of the film as the production cost alone. You're also forgetting that the theaters get to keep approximately one-third of the value of the ticket sales and only approximately 66% of the ticket sales go to the production company.

On the other hand, it's also very much worth considering that Sony sometimes does things with Spider-Man that Marvel doesn't like. Marvel Studios is very particular about what happens in their universe and having Sony be able to make contrary decisions is a complication that has frustrated Marvel. For example, a Sony rep repeatedly insinuated that Venom could end up in the MCU in spite of the fact that Kevin feige was very much not happy about this idea.

Money wise you make some biiiig mistakes:
1. You don't count the advertising const, sometimes they are as big as the production costs.
2. From that BoxOffice money 25% goes to the cinemas, and in china even 50%.

So from the BoxOffice revenue first you have to subtract 50% from Chinas money and 25% from the rest, then you have to subtract the production costs and the advertising costs. After that you can share the remaining money between the companys or get a clue how much movies they have to made. And not every movie goes to 1.2e9$!!
